
[1]elegy

   EL'EGY, n. [L. elegia; Gr. to speak or utter.; L. lugeo. The verbs may
   have a common origin, for to speak and to cry out in wailing are only
   modifications of the same act, to throw out the voice with more or less
   vehemence.]

   1. A mournful or plaintive poem, or a funeral song; a poem or a song
   expressive of sorrow and lamentation.

   2. A short poem without points or affected elegancies.
